00:08:07.150 --> 00:08:10.994
- Okay, next is Erik Jorgensen.

00:08:10.994 --> 00:08:15.994
Can you speculate on what
controls ultra-fast endocytosis?

00:08:16.281 --> 00:08:18.730
At the different temperatures.

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:22.899
Is it ATP, or enzymes, what do you think

00:08:22.899 --> 00:08:27.420
is causing that switch in
the mode of endocytosis?

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:31.757
- Right, so we think that
the most likely change

00:08:31.757 --> 00:08:34.600
is in the lipid, the nature of the lipid.

00:08:34.600 --> 00:08:36.480
So as you cool lipids,

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:40.288
they will eventually go
into a gel-like state,

00:08:40.288 --> 00:08:43.860
which will disallow the
sort of shape changes

00:08:43.860 --> 00:08:45.640
that we think are going on.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:49.810
In particular PIP2 shows some
very bizarre interactions

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:53.530
between moving between room
temperature and 37 degrees,

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:55.960
so the fluidity increases.

00:08:55.960 --> 00:08:58.550
And so that has something
to do with the head group.

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:00.408
The second thing we think that is going on

00:09:00.408 --> 00:09:02.892
is that the fatty acid tails

00:09:02.892 --> 00:09:04.720
that are anchored in the membrane

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:06.550
also are having a strong effect,

00:09:06.550 --> 00:09:11.550
and so particularly for, so
nematodes live at 20 degrees,

00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:13.140
that's not a problem.

00:09:13.140 --> 00:09:15.680
But if you raise an animal at 25 degrees

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:18.870
and you drop it to 20 degrees
it can't move anymore.

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:23.330
If you raise an animal at
15 degrees, it moves fine.

00:09:23.330 --> 00:09:28.330
And so what we are finding is
that fatty acid desaturases

00:09:28.710 --> 00:09:33.710
are what allows these animals
to move better at 15 degrees.

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:36.540
So in the end we think it's going to be

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:40.200
the head groups of the lipids
and the fatty acid tails.

