teams of undergraduates,

00:15:45.700 --> 00:15:47.712
supervised by the most effective

00:15:47.712 --> 00:15:51.160
graduate student or postdoc,

00:15:51.160 --> 00:15:55.591
who manages people kinda like
a McDonald's crew or whatever,

00:15:55.591 --> 00:16:00.510
to actually get the ground truth.

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:04.920
Then it involves, usually,
using big computers.

00:16:04.920 --> 00:16:08.250
Expensive, cycle supercomputers.

00:16:08.250 --> 00:16:13.250
So all the ER in a single Purkinje cell,

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:18.470
done that way, initially
for us, which I didn't show,

00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:21.220
was a million CPU hours,

00:16:21.220 --> 00:16:24.980
between the training the algorithm

00:16:24.980 --> 00:16:26.640
and then executing on it.

00:16:27.670 --> 00:16:31.610
That, with computer graphics cards, GPUs,

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:34.730
once the software that
you've decided works,

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:39.140
is shown to work properly, is ported,

00:16:39.140 --> 00:16:40.891
and then it can be made available

00:16:40.891 --> 00:16:44.430
on a small group of machines

00:16:44.430 --> 00:16:48.370
that might cost a laboratory
10, $15,000 to put together.

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:50.690
So I think that's the
direction that it goes.

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:54.680
But right now, for example,
Jenalia is relying on Google

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:56.950
to do them a big favor.

00:16:59.728 --> 00:17:04.728
Okay, so, that's the
machine learning question.

00:17:06.260 --> 00:17:09.070
Now, this one is for Philipp.

00:17:10.630 --> 00:17:13.770
Do you think you could
add 4Pi capabilities

00:17:13.770 --> 00:17:16.030
to your four-sided light sheet system?

00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:20.030
First you have to explain
to them what that means.

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:23.720
- Sure, so, the short answer
is yes you can do that,

00:17:23.720 --> 00:17:26.270
but it wouldn't make any
sense for our experiments.

00:17:27.513 --> 00:17:30.950
And it's not an obvious
thing, so let me explain.

00:17:30.950 --> 00:17:32.440
I mean basically, the 4Pi approach

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:35.830
just means that you have
two opposing objectives

00:17:35.830 --> 00:17:37.780
aimed at the sample, and so,

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:39.370
actually one of the slides I showed today

00:17:39.370 --> 00:17:43.920
relates to the interest you
might have in that arrangement,

00:17:43.920 --> 00:17:45.601
which is that usually you
don't collect all of the light

00:17:45.601 --> 00:17:49.910
with a conventional objective

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:51.640
with a limited collection angle,

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:53.540
a limited numerical aperture.

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:56.520
So ideally you want the aperture
to be as big as possible,

00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:59.994
and ideally you want to
completely envelope your sample.

00:17:59.994 --> 00:18:01.700
With your detection system

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:04.873
you can really grab all of the photons

00:18:04.873 --> 00:18:08.380
you can get out of the specimen.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:10.940
Which relates to signal
collection efficiency,

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:13.350
but also directly to spatial resolution.

00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:14.690
And so with the 4Pi approach,

00:18:14.690 --> 00:18:17.940
you just have the 4Pi spatial angle,

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:22.230
you have full access to the sample,

00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:23.840
and you can combine it
with other principles,

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:28.280
such as standing structured
patterned illumination,

00:18:28.280 --> 00:18:30.470
where you can go to
sub-wavelength resolution

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:32.260
by just having counter-propagating waves

00:18:32.260 --> 00:18:36.800
set from multiple objectives
that are facing each other.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:38.344
So there's a lot of potential

00:18:38.344 --> 00:18:40.730
in having these more complex arrangements,

00:18:40.730 --> 00:18:42.910
but all of them rely on the concept

00:18:42.910 --> 00:18:45.950
of very precise wavefront control.

00:18:45.950 --> 00:18:48.380
So you're assuming that you will get,

00:18:49.230 --> 00:18:50.850
for example you do the
structured illumination approach,

00:18:50.850 --> 00:18:53.430
that you can get very
precise interference pattern

00:18:53.430 --> 00:18:55.900
inside the sample, so that
you're making an assumption

00:18:55.900 --> 00:18:57.830
about what happens to the
light inside the sample.

00:18:57.830 --> 00:19:00.410
And so all of the
specimens we're looking at,

00:19:00.410 --> 00:19:03.540
the drosophila larvae, the
zebrafish, the zebrafish brains,

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:05.820
zebrafish brain might
be probably the closest

00:19:05.820 --> 00:19:09.310
to making this possible, but even there,

00:19:09.310 --> 00:19:11.830
we are really perturbing the beams,

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:12.663
we are perturbing the wavefront.

00:19:12.663 --> 00:19:15.740
And the errors that we
accumulate in the wavefront

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:18.440
are a much larger order of magnitude

00:19:18.440 --> 00:19:21.880
than what level of precise
spatial control you would need

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:25.846
in order to get the resolution
enhancing effects to work.

00:19:25.846 --> 00:19:27.870
And so for the most part
we just don't really have

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:32.870
enough penetration and control
to use these approaches.

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:35.018
So in the future you could
potentially improve this

00:19:35.018 --> 00:19:37.236
with adaptive optics techniques.

00:19:37.236 --> 00:19:39.568
So you can sort of bend
the light back into shape

00:19:39.568 --> 00:19:42.035
to some extent by mapping this out.

00:19:42.035 --> 00:19:44.390
But then there's still the
problem of light scattering

00:19:44.390 --> 00:19:46.620
and so on that is much harder to resolve,

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:49.350
so I think it's an interesting
direction for the future

00:19:49.350 --> 00:19:51.730
but right now sort of like
not the most obvious thing

00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:53.480
that we would want to push forward.

00:19:54.820 --> 00:19:56.810
- Have you looked at axons in the vicinity

00:19:56.810 --> 00:19:59.610
of different types of plaques
in the Alzheimer brains?

00:20:00.680 --> 00:20:05.680
- Okay, well, I'm not the
person in Alzheimer disease,

00:20:06.130 --> 00:20:10.840
so we didn't go into,
very much, the plaques,

00:20:14.430 --> 00:20:18.240
so there's controversy whether or not,

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:23.810
which, axon or dendrites
have more neuritis.

00:20:26.129 --> 00:20:28.700
I like that debate.

00:20:28.700 --> 00:20:32.440
So, yes, actually I have to confess,

00:20:32.440 --> 00:20:35.540
we tried to look at the axon,

00:20:35.540 --> 00:20:39.400
so the involvement of the
axon in the plaque formation,

00:20:40.914 --> 00:20:45.914
but we didn't do that very much yet.

00:20:46.830 --> 00:20:51.310
But I'm glad somebody asked me.

00:20:53.698 --> 00:20:54.531
(audience laughing)

00:20:54.531 --> 00:20:55.770
We hope to do it.

00:20:57.580 --> 00:20:59.888
- I asked. (laughing)

00:20:59.888 --> 00:21:02.888
(audience laughing)

00:21:09.340 --> 00:21:14.220
- So, we tried to distinguish
the axon and the dendrites

00:21:14.220 --> 00:21:19.220
by some ways, and we didn't
get any good, the antibodies,

00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:23.890
but we need that, you can do it.

00:21:24.850 --> 00:21:28.170
- So, to turn this into
a brief discussion,

00:21:28.170 --> 00:21:30.593
so part of the problem is that the axons

00:21:30.593 --> 00:21:33.910
that go to the vicinity
of the neuritic plaques,

00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:36.870
this is from analyzing biopsy samples

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:39.150
that we did 35 years ago,

00:21:40.550 --> 00:21:44.910
is that of course the
microtubules have depolymerized,

00:21:44.910 --> 00:21:48.470
and tau is now stuck in the soma,

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:51.070
so the markers that you'd normally use

00:21:51.070 --> 00:21:54.150
to say that's an axon are not there,

00:21:54.150 --> 00:21:56.820
but if you look ultrastructurally,

00:21:56.820 --> 00:22:01.820
the plaque area is toxic to the axons.

00:22:02.010 --> 00:22:04.380
And then you have retrograde degeneration.

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:09.480
So, if there were another marker,

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:11.400
rather than the traditional markers,

00:22:11.400 --> 00:22:14.190
or if you could do it with an animal

00:22:14.190 --> 00:22:17.790
that had some sort of labeled
lipids of the membrane,

00:22:18.740 --> 00:22:21.280
you might see it in a more effective way

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:24.610
than the small samples that we did in the,

00:22:24.610 --> 00:22:26.380
I would call it the dark ages.

00:22:27.318 --> 00:22:29.710
- So maybe I add one more thing.

00:22:29.710 --> 00:22:33.430
So we are now more interested
in the diffused plaques

00:22:33.430 --> 00:22:34.990
than the cored plaques.

00:22:34.990 --> 00:22:39.450
So the cored plaques have
very nice, clear boundaries,

00:22:39.450 --> 00:22:44.450
so maybe proximity can
be analyzed in depth.

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:51.260
But diffuse plaques have
very ambiguous boundaries,

00:22:51.570 --> 00:22:53.109
it's more of a challenge

00:22:53.109 --> 00:22:57.860
concerning the interaction
with other objects.

00:22:57.860 --> 00:23:02.300
So, yep, cored plaques
are maybe a good target.

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:05.800
- Yeah, longer discussion,
maybe, with Dai I or something.

00:23:07.630 --> 00:23:10.290
So this, I think this
